#:proof{:extraction {:phases {:propose "Iterate finite ε-nets. For each `ε_k = 2^{-k}`, cover the space with finitely many ε-balls and choose one containing infinitely many terms of the given sequence. The nested sequence of balls yields a subsequence with diameters tending to zero, hence a Cauchy subsequence. Completeness converts Cauchy subsequences into convergent subsequences, delivering sequential compactness and thus compactness.", :execute "1. Let `(x_n)` be any sequence in a totally bounded, complete metric space `X`. Set `ε_k = 2^{-k}`.  \n2. Total boundedness gives a finite `ε₁`-cover; pick a ball `B₁` that contains infinitely many `x_n`. Restrict to those indices.  \n3. Inside `B₁`, total boundedness again gives a finite `ε₂`-cover; choose `B₂ ⊆ B₁` containing infinitely many remaining terms. Continue inductively, obtaining nested balls `B_k` of radius `ε_k`.  \n4. Choose strictly increasing indices `n_k` with `x_{n_k} ∈ B_k`. If `i > j`, then `x_{n_i}` and `x_{n_j}` both lie in `B_j`, whose diameter is at most `2^{-j+1}`, so the subsequence `(x_{n_k})` is Cauchy.  \n5. Completeness of `X` forces `(x_{n_k})` to converge in `X`. Hence every sequence has a convergent subsequence: `X` is sequentially compact, and therefore compact (metric-space equivalence).", :integrate "- The ε-net diagonal argument is the standard proof that “precompact + complete ⇒ compact” in any uniform space; it’s used in constructing the completion of a uniform space, in Arzelà–Ascoli–type theorems, and in functional analysis when proving that bounded sequences of equicontinuous functions have convergent subsequences.  \n- On exams, this technique pairs naturally with questions about totally bounded subsets of Banach spaces, equicontinuity, and the difference between local compactness and mere boundedness."}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 3, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :classification :proved, :reclassification-reason "Post-hoc: zero sorry with substantive declarations", :output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (explicitly references the metric space \\(X\\), total boundedness, completeness, and compactness) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the formal target assumes only total boundedness + completeness and concludes compactness) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the EDN statements alone fully encode the claim and the helper lemma about extracting Cauchy subsequences) · notes: helper lemma isolates the sequential-compactness step, which is the core of the textbook proof.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Use total boundedness + completeness to deduce compactness.\"\n :terms [{:name \"totally bounded\"\n          :meaning \"Every ε>0 admits a finite ε-net.\"\n          :needed-because \"This is the source of Cauchy subsequences in arbitrary sequences.\"}\n         {:name \"completeness\"\n          :meaning \"Every Cauchy sequence converges.\"\n          :needed-because \"Once the totally bounded subsequence is Cauchy, completeness gives a limit in X.\"}\n         {:name \"sequential compactness\"\n          :meaning \"Every sequence has a convergent subsequence.\"\n          :needed-because \"In metric spaces, sequential compactness ⇔ compactness, so proving sequential compactness suffices.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"totally_bounded_complete_compact\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 builds a nested sequence of ε-nets to extract a Cauchy subsequence\"\n             :why-this-now \"The standard proof uses the finite ε-nets to choose a subsequence shrinking the diameter; completeness then yields a convergent subsequence.\"\n             :lean-target \"totallyBoundedSpace.compact_of_complete\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already has lemmas about totally bounded sets/metric spaces and sequential compactness, so the formal proof should track the textbook argument.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Every totally bounded complete metric space is compact.\"\n             :formal-name \"totally_bounded_complete_compact\"\n             :formal-target \"For any metric space X, if X is totally bounded and complete, then CompactSpace X.\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"This is the statement we must prove.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"totally_bounded_complete_compact\"\n              :formal-statement \"TotallyBounded X ∧ CompleteSpace X → CompactSpace X.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Stage 1 claim after the sequential compactness argument\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"sequential_compactness_of_totally_bounded\"\n              :formal-statement \"In a totally bounded metric space every sequence admits a Cauchy subsequence.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Stage 1 subsection extracting the Cauchy subsequence\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\nImplemented the formal statement “totally bounded + complete ⇒ compact” in the frame-local Lean module and synchronized every artifact with the finished proof. The key addition is the theorem `totally_bounded_complete_compact` in `apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T95A03/Apm_v2_t95A03_1775011813898/Main.lean:12-22`, which specializes Mathlib’s uniform-space lemma `isCompact_iff_totallyBounded_isComplete` to the whole space and repackages `IsCompact univ` as a `CompactSpace`. I then refreshed `execute.md`, `proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, and `changelog.edn` under the frame directory so Stage 3/4 and the Lean alignment now reflect the completed argument. `lake build ApmCanaries.Frames.T95A03.Apm_v2_t95A03_1775011813898.Main` passes cleanly.\n\n**Why it’s hard**  \n- “Totally bounded” sounds like ordinary boundedness, so it is tempting to try Euclidean-only results such as Heine–Borel; the trap is ignoring general metric spaces where closed-and-bounded is not enough.  \n- Students also forget that compactness in metric spaces is equivalent to sequential compactness, so they chase open covers instead of controlling arbitrary sequences.  \n- Constructing the right subsequence requires juggling infinitely many finite ε-covers; without a systematic shrinking process, it is easy to lose a subsequence entirely.\n\n**Key insight**  \nIterate finite ε-nets. For each `ε_k = 2^{-k}`, cover the space with finitely many ε-balls and choose one containing infinitely many terms of the given sequence. The nested sequence of balls yields a subsequence with diameters tending to zero, hence a Cauchy subsequence. Completeness converts Cauchy subsequences into convergent subsequences, delivering sequential compactness and thus compactness.\n\n**Complete proof**  \n1. Let `(x_n)` be any sequence in a totally bounded, complete metric space `X`. Set `ε_k = 2^{-k}`.  \n2. Total boundedness gives a finite `ε₁`-cover; pick a ball `B₁` that contains infinitely many `x_n`. Restrict to those indices.  \n3. Inside `B₁`, total boundedness again gives a finite `ε₂`-cover; choose `B₂ ⊆ B₁` containing infinitely many remaining terms. Continue inductively, obtaining nested balls `B_k` of radius `ε_k`.  \n4. Choose strictly increasing indices `n_k` with `x_{n_k} ∈ B_k`. If `i > j`, then `x_{n_i}` and `x_{n_j}` both lie in `B_j`, whose diameter is at most `2^{-j+1}`, so the subsequence `(x_{n_k})` is Cauchy.  \n5. Completeness of `X` forces `(x_{n_k})` to converge in `X`. Hence every sequence has a convergent subsequence: `X` is sequentially compact, and therefore compact (metric-space equivalence).\n\n**Lean 4 formalization**  \n- Main theorem: `totally_bounded_complete_compact` (`apm-lean/.../Main.lean:12-22`). It assumes `[PseudoMetricSpace X]`, `[CompleteSpace X]`, and `TotallyBounded (univ : Set X)`, and concludes `CompactSpace X` by invoking `isCompact_iff_totallyBounded_isComplete` on `univ`.  \n- Build: `lake build ApmCanaries.Frames.T95A03.Apm_v2_t95A03_1775011813898.Main`.\n\n**What connects**  \n- The ε-net diagonal argument is the standard proof that “precompact + complete ⇒ compact” in any uniform space; it’s used in constructing the completion of a uniform space, in Arzelà–Ascoli–type theorems, and in functional analysis when proving that bounded sequences of equicontinuous functions have convergent subsequences.  \n- On exams, this technique pairs naturally with questions about totally bounded subsets of Banach spaces, equicontinuity, and the difference between local compactness and mere boundedness.", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/T95A03/Apm_v2_t95A03_1775011813898", :frame/id "apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T02:50:13.920952Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.T95A03.Apm_v2_t95A03_1775011813898", :proof/problem-id "t95A03", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/t95A03/apm-v2-t95A03-1775011813898/